## Description {#details}

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/gsymcreator">GsymCreator</a> is used to emit GSYM data to a stand alone file or section within a file.

The <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/gsymcreator">GsymCreator</a> is designed to be used in 3 stages:
<ul>
<li>Create <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> objects and add them</li>
<li>Finalize the <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/gsymcreator">GsymCreator</a> object</li>
<li>Save to file or section</li>
</ul>


The first stage involves creating <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> objects from another source of information like compiler debug info metadata, DWARF or Breakpad files. <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/any">Any</a> strings in the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> or contained information, like <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/inlineinfo">InlineInfo</a> or <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/linetable">LineTable</a> objects, should get the string table offsets by calling GsymCreator::insertString(...). <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/any">Any</a> file indexes that are needed should be obtained by calling GsymCreator::insertFile(...). All of the function calls in <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/gsymcreator">GsymCreator</a> are thread safe. This allows multiple threads to create and add <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> objects while parsing debug information.

Once all of the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> objects have been added, the GsymCreator::finalize(...) must be called prior to saving. This function will sort the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> objects, finalize the string table, and do any other passes on the information needed to prepare the information to be saved.

Once the object has been finalized, it can be saved to a file or section.

ENCODING

GSYM files are designed to be memory mapped into a process as shared, read only data, and used as is.

The GSYM file format when in a stand alone file consists of:
<ul>
<li><a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/header">Header</a></li>
<li>Address Table</li>
<li><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/function">Function</a> Info Offsets</li>
<li>File Table</li>
<li>String Table</li>
<li><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/function">Function</a> Info Data</li>
</ul>


HEADER

The header is fully described in &quot;llvm/DebugInfo/GSYM/Header.h&quot;.

ADDRESS TABLE

The address table immediately follows the header in the file and consists of <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/header/#ae56c0257076bd0b9c1a4f42671eb03f0">Header.NumAddresses</a> address offsets. These offsets are sorted and can be binary searched for efficient lookups. Addresses in the address table are stored as offsets from a 64 bit base address found in <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/header/#af3a0fa4fd0587b1bcb2e1979bbe3c747">Header.BaseAddress</a>. This allows the address table to contain 8, 16, or 32 offsets. This allows the address table to not require full 64 bit addresses for each address. The resulting GSYM size is smaller and causes fewer pages to be touched during address lookups when the address table is smaller. The size of the address offsets in the address table is specified in the header in <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/header/#a34f83b8e1b9a91f2e306a9d0df969a5b">Header.AddrOffSize</a>. The first offset in the address table is aligned to <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/header/#a34f83b8e1b9a91f2e306a9d0df969a5b">Header.AddrOffSize</a> alignment to ensure efficient access when loaded into memory.

FUNCTION INFO OFFSETS TABLE

The function info offsets table immediately follows the address table and consists of <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/header/#ae56c0257076bd0b9c1a4f42671eb03f0">Header.NumAddresses</a> 32 bit file offsets: one for each address in the address table. This data is aligned to a 4 byte boundary. The offsets in this table are the relative offsets from the start offset of the GSYM header and point to the function info data for each address in the address table. Keeping this data separate from the address table helps to reduce the number of pages that are touched when address lookups occur on a GSYM file.

FILE TABLE

The file table immediately follows the function info offsets table. The encoding of the FileTable is:

struct FileTable &#123; uint32&#95;t Count; <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/fileentry">FileEntry</a> Files&#91;&#93;; &#125;;

The file table starts with a 32 bit count of the number of files that are used in all of the function info, followed by that number of <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/fileentry">FileEntry</a> structures. The file table is aligned to a 4 byte boundary, Each file in the file table is represented with a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/fileentry">FileEntry</a> structure. See &quot;llvm/DebugInfo/GSYM/FileEntry.h&quot; for details.

STRING TABLE

The string table follows the file table in stand alone GSYM files and contains all strings for everything contained in the GSYM file. <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/any">Any</a> string data should be added to the string table and any references to strings inside GSYM information must be stored as 32 bit string table offsets into this string table. The string table always starts with an empty string at offset zero and is followed by any strings needed by the GSYM information. The start of the string table is not aligned to any boundary.

FUNCTION INFO DATA

The function info data is the payload that contains information about the address that is being looked up. It contains all of the encoded <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> objects. Each encoded <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a>&#39;s data is pointed to by an entry in the <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/function">Function</a> Info Offsets Table. For details on the exact encoding of <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> objects, see &quot;llvm/DebugInfo/GSYM/FunctionInfo.h&quot;.

### createSegment() {#a5a00b6c05d78359948c41de0ee1f20a4}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>llvm::Expected&lt; std::unique&#95;ptr&lt; GsymCreator &gt; &gt; GsymCreator::createSegment (uint64&#95;t SegmentSize, size&#95;t &amp; FuncIdx) const</>}>
Create a segmented GSYM creator starting with function info index <em>FuncIdx</em>.

This function will create a <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/gsymcreator">GsymCreator</a> object that will encode into roughly <em>SegmentSize</em> bytes and return it. It is used by the private saveSegments(...) function and also is used by the GSYM unit tests to test segmenting of GSYM files. The returned <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/gsymcreator">GsymCreator</a> can be finalized and encoded.

<SectionUser title="Returns">

### IsValidTextAddress() {#aed7eb12c998221cb39a6a3d96e9a0e56}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>bool GsymCreator::IsValidTextAddress (uint64&#95;t Addr) const</>}>
<a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/check">Check</a> if an address is a valid code address.

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/any">Any</a> functions whose addresses do not exist within these function bounds will not be converted into the final GSYM. This allows the object file to figure out the valid file address ranges of all the code sections and ensure we don&#39;t add invalid functions to the final output. Many linkers have issues when dead stripping functions from DWARF debug info where they set the DW&#95;AT&#95;low&#95;pc to zero, but newer DWARF has the DW&#95;AT&#95;high&#95;pc as an offset from the DW&#95;AT&#95;low&#95;pc and these size attributes have no relocations that can be applied. This results in DWARF where many functions have an DW&#95;AT&#95;low&#95;pc of zero and a valid offset size for DW&#95;AT&#95;high&#95;pc. If we extract all valid ranges from an object file that are marked with executable permissions, we can properly ensure that these functions are removed.


<ParametersList title="Parameters">
<ParametersListItem name="Addr">An address to check.</ParametersListItem>
</ParametersList>

<SectionUser title="Returns">
True if the address is in the valid text ranges or if no valid text ranges have been set, false otherwise.
</SectionUser>

Declaration at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/gsymcreator-h/#l00448">448</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/gsymcreator-h">GsymCreator.h</a>, definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/gsymcreator-cpp/#l00424">424</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/gsymcreator-cpp">GsymCreator.cpp</a>.

  labels = {["inline"]}>
Set the base address to use for the GSYM file.

Setting the base address to use for the GSYM file. Object files typically get loaded from a base address when the OS loads them into memory. Using GSYM files for symbolication becomes easier if the base address in the GSYM header is the same address as it allows addresses to be easily slid and allows symbolication without needing to find the original base address in the original object file.

### calculateHeaderAndTableSize() {#a184a8738d7e06598e2b134fbe8de1db5}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>uint64&#95;t GsymCreator::calculateHeaderAndTableSize () const</>}>
Calculate the byte size of the GSYM header and tables sizes.

This function will calculate the exact size in bytes of the encocded GSYM for the following items:
<ul>
<li>The GSYM header</li>
<li>The Address offset table</li>
<li>The Address info offset table</li>
<li>The file table</li>
<li>The string table</li>
</ul>


This is used to help split GSYM files into segments.


<SectionUser title="Returns">
Size in bytes the GSYM header and tables.
</SectionUser>

Copy a file from <em>SrcGC</em> into this object.

Copy a file from <em>SrcGC</em> by file index into this GSYM creator. Files consist of two string table entries, one for the directory and one for the filename, this function will copy any needed strings ensure the file is uniqued within this object. If a file already exists in this GSYM creator the uniqued index will be returned, else the stirngs will be copied and the new file index will be returned.

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>uint8&#95;t GsymCreator::getAddressOffsetSize () const</>}>
Get the size of an address offset in the address offset table.

GSYM files store offsets from the base address in the address offset table and we store the size of the address offsets in the GSYM header. This function will calculate the size in bytes of these address offsets based on the current contents of the GSYM file.

### saveSegments() {#a275c1ae3dda520ae8831fea5fefd346b}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>llvm::Error GsymCreator::saveSegments (<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/stringref">StringRef</a> Path, <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ae1e26e57357947b25e392fd18ab000db">llvm::endianness</a> ByteOrder, uint64&#95;t SegmentSize) const</>}>
Save this GSYM file into segments that are roughly <em>SegmentSize</em> in size.

When segemented GSYM files are saved to disk, they will use <em>Path</em> as a prefix and then have the first function info address appended to the path when each segment is saved. Each segmented GSYM file has a only the strings and files that are needed to save the function infos that are in each segment. These smaller files are easy to compress and download separately and allow for efficient lookups with very large GSYM files and segmenting them allows servers to download only the segments that are needed.


<ParametersList title="Parameters">
<ParametersListItem name="Path">The path prefix to use when saving the GSYM files.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="ByteOrder">The endianness to use when saving the file.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="SegmentSize">The size in bytes to segment the GSYM file into.</ParametersListItem>
</ParametersList>
